  <section>
    <h2>Vaccine Protection Tailored to Your Pet's Life</h2>
    <p>
      Vaccines are one of the most effective tools we have to protect your pet from dangerous — and sometimes deadly — infectious diseases. But not every pet needs the same vaccines, and a one-size-fits-all approach isn't good medicine. At Healthy Paws Animal Hospital in Lake in the Hills, IL, we create <strong>customized vaccination protocols</strong> based on your pet's age, breed, health status, and lifestyle. Your dog who hikes every weekend has different needs than your indoor-only cat — and we treat them that way.
    </p>
    <p>
      Every vaccine visit is conducted using <strong>gentle, low-stress techniques</strong> to keep your pet calm and comfortable. From careful handling to strategic treat distraction, we make the experience as stress-free as possible.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Dog Vaccines</h2>

    <h3>Core Vaccines for Dogs</h3>
    <p>
      Core vaccines are recommended for all dogs regardless of lifestyle. They protect against widespread, highly contagious, or life-threatening diseases:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Rabies</strong> — required by Illinois state law. Fatal if contracted. Protects both your pet and your family.</li>
      <li><strong>DHPP (Distemper, Hepatitis, Parvovirus, Parainfluenza)</strong> — a combination vaccine that protects against four serious viral diseases. Parvovirus alone is often fatal in unvaccinated puppies.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Lifestyle Vaccines for Dogs</h3>
    <p>
      These vaccines are recommended based on your dog's exposure risk. We'll discuss which ones make sense during your pet's <a href="/wellness-exams-lake-in-the-hills-il/">wellness exam</a>:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Bordetella (Kennel Cough)</strong> — recommended for dogs who visit boarding facilities, doggy daycare, grooming salons, or dog parks</li>
      <li><strong>Leptospirosis</strong> — a bacterial disease spread through wildlife urine and standing water. Common in suburban areas like Lake in the Hills where deer and raccoons are present.</li>
      <li><strong>Lyme Disease</strong> — transmitted by ticks. Recommended for dogs who spend time in wooded or grassy areas in McHenry and Kane counties.</li>
      <li><strong>Canine Influenza (H3N2/H3N8)</strong> — highly contagious respiratory virus. Increasingly required by boarding and daycare facilities across Illinois.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Cat Vaccines</h2>

    <h3>Core Vaccines for Cats</h3>
    <p>
      All cats — including indoor-only cats — should receive core vaccines. Viruses can be carried into your home on shoes, clothing, and even other pets:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Rabies</strong> — required by Illinois law for all cats. Bats and wildlife can enter homes, making this essential even for indoor cats.</li>
      <li><strong>FVRCP (Feline Viral Rhinotracheitis, Calicivirus, Panleukopenia)</strong> — protects against three common and serious feline diseases. Panleukopenia (feline distemper) has a very high mortality rate in unvaccinated cats.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Lifestyle Vaccines for Cats</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>FeLV (Feline Leukemia Virus)</strong> — recommended for cats who go outdoors, live in multi-cat households, or have contact with cats of unknown FeLV status. FeLV suppresses the immune system and can lead to cancer.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Our <a href="/cat-vet-lake-in-the-hills-il/">cat-friendly veterinary approach</a> means feline patients get a calmer, quieter exam experience — including vaccinations.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Puppy and Kitten Vaccine Schedules</h2>
    <p>
      Young pets need a series of vaccines spaced 3 to 4 weeks apart to build proper immunity. Maternal antibodies from nursing can interfere with vaccine effectiveness, so a single shot isn't enough — the series ensures protection kicks in at the right time.
    </p>

    <h3>Typical Puppy Schedule</h3>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>6-8 weeks:</strong> First DHPP, start deworming</li>
      <li><strong>10-12 weeks:</strong> Second DHPP, bordetella, begin leptospirosis if appropriate</li>
      <li><strong>14-16 weeks:</strong> Third DHPP, rabies, leptospirosis booster, Lyme if appropriate</li>
      <li><strong>12-16 months:</strong> First adult boosters for all vaccines</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Typical Kitten Schedule</h3>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>6-8 weeks:</strong> First FVRCP, start deworming</li>
      <li><strong>10-12 weeks:</strong> Second FVRCP, FeLV if appropriate</li>
      <li><strong>14-16 weeks:</strong> Third FVRCP, rabies, FeLV booster if started</li>
      <li><strong>12-16 months:</strong> First adult boosters</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Every schedule is adjusted based on your pet's individual needs. If you've adopted a pet with an unknown vaccine history, we'll create a catch-up plan to get them protected as quickly and safely as possible.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why We Don't Use a One-Size-Fits-All Approach</h2>
    <p>
      Some clinics give every pet the same set of vaccines on the same schedule. We don't think that's the best medicine. Over-vaccinating adds unnecessary cost and — while rare — increases the chance of adverse reactions. Under-vaccinating leaves gaps in protection that put your pet at risk.
    </p>
    <p>
      Our veterinarians evaluate each patient individually. We consider:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Your pet's age, breed, and overall health</li>
      <li>Lifestyle factors — indoor vs. outdoor, boarding, travel, multi-pet household</li>
      <li>Local disease prevalence in the Lake in the Hills and McHenry County area</li>
      <li>Previous vaccine history and any past reactions</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      For pets with a solid vaccine history, we also offer <strong>titer testing</strong> — a blood test that measures existing antibody levels. If your pet already has strong immunity from previous vaccines, a titer test can confirm that a booster isn't needed yet. It's an evidence-based way to avoid unnecessary vaccines while ensuring your pet stays protected.
    </p>
  </section>

